      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Brisbane Property When You Owe More Than It Is Worth
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Negative equity is uncommon in Brisbane's inner east, but it does happen. Understanding your options, your obligations, and what lenders actually require makes the process far less daunting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Negative equity is the situation where the outstanding balance on a mortgage exceeds the current market value of the property. If you sold today and the proceeds were applied to the loan, there would still be a debt remaining after settlement. In Brisbane's inner east, this is a relatively rare situation: the sustained price growth across suburbs like Morningside, Camp Hill, Bulimba, and Hawthorne has meant that most owners who have held a property for more than a few years are sitting on substantial equity, not a deficit. But it does occur, particularly for owners who purchased near the peak of a cycle, bought with a very small deposit, or have drawn down heavily against a line of credit secured on the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can you sell when you are in negative equity?</h2>
      <p>Yes. There is no legal barrier to listing or selling a property where the mortgage balance exceeds the market value. What changes is the settlement process: because the sale proceeds will not be enough to discharge the mortgage in full, the lender must agree to release the security over the property in exchange for partial repayment of the loan. The lender holds a registered mortgage over the title, and that mortgage cannot be discharged without the lender's consent.</p>

      <p>This means the first step for any owner in this situation is to approach their lender before listing, not after. Disclosing the position and seeking the lender's agreement to proceed is not optional. If you list and sell without lender consent, you face the prospect of reaching settlement with no way to hand over clear title to the buyer. That is a breach of contract and creates significant legal exposure for both the seller and the agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The process: what lenders actually require</h2>
      <p>When you approach your lender to disclose the shortfall and seek approval to sell, they will generally ask you to demonstrate that the proposed sale price represents fair market value for the property. In practice, this means providing a current market appraisal or a formal valuation from a registered property valuer. The lender needs to satisfy itself that the sale is not a below-market transaction that is artificially reducing the proceeds available to reduce the debt.</p>

      <p>Once the lender is satisfied that the sale price is reasonable, most will agree to proceed on the basis that they will receive the full net sale proceeds after agent commission, legal fees, and other settlement costs, and that the remaining shortfall will be dealt with separately. The lender will typically confirm this arrangement in writing before the property is listed, and that written confirmation should be in place before contracts are exchanged with a buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to the debt that remains after settlement?</h2>
      <p>Selling the property does not extinguish the debt. The seller remains personally liable for the difference between the net sale proceeds and the outstanding loan balance. This is one of the most important things to understand before deciding to sell: the transaction clears the asset, but the liability persists until it is paid.</p>

      <p>Lenders handle the remaining shortfall in several ways. The most common outcome is that the lender allows the seller to repay the shortfall over time through a structured repayment plan, typically converted into a personal loan or an unsecured debt arrangement. In some cases, where the lender believes a forced sale would produce a worse outcome, they may agree to a short sale: accepting less than the full mortgage balance as full satisfaction of the debt. Short sales are relatively uncommon and are typically only considered where the alternative is a lengthy forced sale process that would cost the lender more in legal and enforcement costs than accepting the shortfall now.</p>

      <p>If a lender agrees to a short sale and writes off part of the debt, that arrangement may be reported to credit agencies and could affect the seller's credit record and future borrowing capacity. Before agreeing to any arrangement that involves the lender accepting less than the full balance, you should take independent legal and financial advice. The implications vary depending on the size of the shortfall, the lender, and your personal financial position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The costs of selling, and how they affect the shortfall</h2>
      <p>Selling a property in negative equity does not exempt you from the usual costs of selling. Agent commission is still payable. Conveyancing and legal fees are still payable. If you have engaged a stylist or carried out any pre-sale preparation, those costs are still your responsibility. Every dollar spent on selling costs is a dollar added to the shortfall: the net proceeds available to reduce the loan balance are reduced by the selling costs before they reach the lender.</p>

      <p>This makes it important to understand the full cost of the transaction before committing to sell. A property worth $720,000 with an outstanding mortgage of $780,000 has a gross shortfall of $60,000. After agent commission of around $18,000 to $22,000 and legal fees of $2,000 to $3,000, the net shortfall to be carried forward may be $80,000 or more. That is the actual liability you are managing, and it needs to be weighed against the alternatives before deciding to sell.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Alternatives to selling</h2>
      <p>Whether selling is the right call depends heavily on the size of the shortfall, the rental income the property can generate, and your personal financial position. For some owners, holding the property and renting it out to cover the mortgage while values recover is a more viable path than crystallising the loss now. If the property can be rented for enough to cover or come close to the mortgage repayments, the holding cost of waiting for values to recover may be lower than the cost of selling and carrying a shortfall debt forward.</p>

      <p>Refinancing is another option worth exploring before deciding to sell. If the current loan has a high interest rate or unfavourable terms, refinancing to reduce the monthly repayment may make the holding position more sustainable. Lenders will typically need to see that the refinancing makes financial sense and that you can service the new loan, but if your income supports it, refinancing can buy time for values to recover without crystallising the loss.</p>

      <p>Making additional repayments to rebuild equity is the third option, though it requires available cash flow. Even modest additional repayments over a period of one to three years can shift the loan-to-value ratio enough to bring the property back into positive equity territory, at which point a standard sale becomes straightforward again.</p>

      <p>None of these options is universally right. Which one makes sense depends on your income, your cash reserves, the rental demand in your suburb, and how far the current value is below the mortgage balance. A financial adviser with property experience can model the numbers for your specific situation and help you compare the true cost of each path.</p>

